ws how American religious diversity works by closely investigating religious advocacy spanning the past century: during the Great Depression, World War II, the civil rights movement, the debates about welfare reform, the recent struggles for immigrant rights and economic equality, and responses to the coronavirus pandemic. The engagement of religious groups in advocacy and counteradvocacy has sharpened arguments about authoritarianism, liberty of conscience, freedom of assembly, human dignity, citizens’ rights, equality, and public health. Wuthnow hones in on key principles of democratic governance and provides a hopeful yet realistic appraisal of what religion can and cannot achieve.At a time when many observers believe American democracy to be in dire need of revitalization, Why Religion Is Good for American Democracy illustrates how religious groups have contributed to this end and how they might continue to do so despite the many challenges faced by the nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDemocracyzUnited StatesxReligious aspects. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aPolitical participationzUnited StatesxReligious aspects. 0aReligion and politicszUnited States. 0aReligious pluralismxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAdvocacy group.  aAdvocacy.  aAfrican Americans.  aAmerican Jewish Congress.  aAmericans.  aAuthoritarianism.  aBaptist World Alliance.  aBaptists.  aBig government.  aBilly Graham.  aBlack church.  aCatholic Church.  aChaplain.  aChristian denomination.  aChristian.  aChristianity Today.  aChristianity.  aChurch World Service.  aCivil society.  aClergy.  aCommunism.  aCommunity organization.  aCongregational church.  aConscientious objector.  aConsideration.  aCriti